# Delivery pipeline

A multi-agent loop that turns a high-level goal into shipped, committed work.
Stack: **{stack_id}**. One issue at a time; the committed issue store is the only
durable state.

## Agents (in `.claude/agents/`)
- **pm** — goal → roadmap + ordered issues; files discovered followups as `proposed`.
- **architect** — system design for one issue; updates docs; hands a plan to the coder.
- **coder** — implements one issue; runs `{test_cmd}` and `{lint_cmd}`.
- **research** — fills context gaps; training data for stable facts, live web search
  for version-specific / post-cutoff / security / pricing / current-best-practice.

Invoke them as subagents via the `Task` tool — never inline the whole pipeline in one
context. The `pipeline-loop` skill orchestrates them per issue.

## Orchestration discipline (RLM / context-as-environment)
The loop is a multi-agent recursion; it follows the project's `recursive-workflows`
conventions: declared outputs only, the scout emits the work-list, adversarial-verify
by default, and depth/calls/budget/timeout guardrails.
- **Bindings discipline — declared outputs only.** A sub-agent's transcript never
  re-enters the orchestrator. Pass an agent the issue *id* and let it read the issue
  file itself; agents write their work into the issue body (Design / Implementation)
  and the workspace, and return a short conclusion — never a transcript dump. Do not
  paste one agent's prose into the next agent's prompt; pass references.
- **The scout emits the work-list (RLM rubric #4).** The decomposition is produced,
  not hardcoded: the `pm` agent *emits* the ordered issue list from the goal and the
  loop reads it from the committed issue store. Never bake a static array of tasks
  into the loop.
- **Adversarial verification by default.** Review is a separate skeptic, not the
  author grading itself — prefer the `reviewer` agent (or a fresh review pass)
  prompted to *refute* the diff against `.claude/rules/`, not to rubber-stamp it.
- **Bounded recursion.** Keep self-delegation shallow (depth-1 is enough); cap total
  delegations; for any `Bash`/external step pass an explicit `timeout`; and assert a
  required CLI/MCP exists before dispatching the agent that needs it (fail fast here,
  not in a doomed child).

## Issue store
- `.claude/roadmap.md` — a generated projection of the issues (do not hand-edit;
  regenerate with `issues.sh roadmap`).
- `.claude/issues/<NNNN>-<slug>.md` — one file per issue. Frontmatter:
  `id, title, status, milestone, kind, depends_on, discovered_by, updated`.
  - `status`: `proposed` | `ready` | `in-progress` | `blocked` | `done`
  - `kind`: `feature` | `bug` | `gap` | `enhancement`
- The helper `.claude/scripts/transcend/pipeline/issues.sh` owns the issue
  lifecycle: it is the ONLY thing that changes `status` and picks the next issue.
  Agents call it; they never edit the `status` field by hand. They DO fill the
  issue **body** (Context/Goal, Design, Implementation, Notes) by editing the file.
  Subcommands: `next`, `list <status>`, `claim <id>`, `done <id>`,
  `block <id> "<reason>"`, `approve <id>`, `roadmap`,
  `new <kind> <slug> --title "..." [--milestone "..."] [--depends-on "NNNN,NNNN"] [--discovered-by NNNN]`.

## Lifecycle
```
proposed --(developer approval)--> ready --(loop claims; deps done)--> in-progress
in-progress --(review passes + commit)--> done
in-progress --(blocker)--> blocked --(unblocked)--> ready
```
- pm (and any agent) create issues as `proposed` for new/discovered work.
- The developer approves `proposed` → `ready` (`issues.sh approve`).
- `pipeline-loop` does `ready` → `in-progress` → `done`.
- architect/coder set `blocked` when they hit a blocker.

## Rules
- **One loop at a time.** `issues.sh claim` is single-flight (lockfile); never run
  two `pipeline-loop`s against the same repo.
- **Resume, don't duplicate.** If an issue is already `in-progress` when the loop
  wakes, finish it — do not claim a new one.
- **Followups are proposals, not detours.** Discovered bugs/gaps go in as `proposed`
  and wait for approval; don't expand the current issue's scope.
- The pipeline adds no blocking hooks; correctness rides on the agents + this rule.
- **Declared outputs only.** Sub-agents return conclusions plus issue-file edits,
  never raw transcripts; the orchestrator passes issue ids and references, not pasted
  prose (context-as-environment).
